<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Contribution without contempt</h2>
  <p>Article One establishes a survival floor: so all may eat. The floor is not naive. It preserves distinctions between need, contribution, refusal, and harm.</p>
  <p>A circle applying this article should begin with material reality: who is hungry, what food exists, what labor is needed, and what harms are destroying the shared capacity to provide. The answer must not humiliate dependence, but it must not ignore predation.</p>
  <p>The practical rule is simple: meet the survival need, then make the conditions visible enough that duty, fraud, incapacity, refusal, and harm can no longer be confused.</p>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> So all may eat</p>
  <p>Article One of The Interdependent Way begins with survival: from each as they will, to each as they have given, so all may eat.</p>
  <p>That is not a slogan for forced labor, and it is not a blank check for neglect. It says food comes first, because politics that cannot feed people has already failed.</p>
  <p>But the footnotes keep the rule honest. Fragility can reveal what the strong missed. Safety exists only by skill, will, vigilance, and luck. False help, empty promises, thieves, liars, and distractions can destroy the comfort and safety they claim to serve.</p>
  <p>The article asks us to feed without contempt, contribute without coercion, and recognize harm before it poisons the table.</p>
</section>
